WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:29.320
I don't get why humans matter.

00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:36.120
It seems that the development of absolute spirit is about absolute spirit.

00:00:36.260 --> 00:00:44.320
All of this movement is about the manifestation and self-realization of absolute spirit, of which we're just kind of byproducts.

00:00:44.700 --> 00:00:50.020
So I don't understand – and I'd be fine with the fact that humans don't matter, right?

00:00:50.060 --> 00:00:52.500
Like I don't think that humans do need to matter.

00:00:52.500 --> 00:01:04.320
But there does seem to be – it doesn't often seem to be explicit, but it does seem to be this implication that the mechanisms that drive absolute spirit also just so happen to drive humans.

00:01:04.480 --> 00:01:05.980
And I don't know why.

00:01:06.020 --> 00:01:19.820
I don't know why there's this mimetic or mirrored process that would say that, okay, this thing that is happening at the level of God, it also just so happens to be running at a smaller level with us.

00:01:19.820 --> 00:01:24.380
And there are oftentimes – I think this is at the bottom of 28.

00:01:25.540 --> 00:01:29.680
So like the last two or three sentences of 28, and this is at the bottom of 16 here.

00:01:29.680 --> 00:01:43.560
So this past existence is the already acquired property of universal spirit, which constitutes the substance of the individual, and hence appears externally to him as his inorganic nature.

00:01:44.220 --> 00:01:56.580
In this respect, formative education, regarded from the side of the individual, consists in his acquiring what thus lies at hand, devouring his inorganic nature and taking possession for it for himself.

00:01:56.980 --> 00:02:08.180
But regarded from the side of universal spirit as substance, this is nothing but its own acquisition of self-consciousness, the bringing about of its own becoming and reflection into itself.

00:02:09.980 --> 00:02:15.200
I don't see the relation – I don't understand the relationship between the two.

00:02:16.100 --> 00:02:18.420
I don't understand why any of this matters for humans.

00:02:18.420 --> 00:02:22.740
I kind of agree with the underlying tone of your question here.

00:02:23.300 --> 00:02:31.900
I would just frame it a little bit differently, which is a massive privileging of human consciousness as the index of spirit.

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:44.620
Well, that was my other question, is why is subjectivity presumed as the er, rather than understand subjectivity as one kind of modality of being among others?

00:02:44.620 --> 00:02:51.020
But it seems the subjectivity has to be presumed as the thing, and it is the totalizing thing of God.

00:02:51.120 --> 00:02:51.920
But sorry, I cut you off.

00:02:52.140 --> 00:02:58.580
Yeah, I mean, I would say that the short answer to that question is humanism.

00:02:59.060 --> 00:03:07.240
The long answer is on 18, where he talks – or sorry, in paragraph 32, where he says,

00:03:07.440 --> 00:03:15.440
the activity of dissolution is the power and work of the understanding, the most astonishing and mightiest power, or rather the absolute power.

00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:24.440
But a different way – in other words, humans possess understanding, which presumably nothing else possesses,

00:03:24.680 --> 00:03:29.220
which is exactly why they're the necessary and essential vehicle for spirit.

00:03:29.780 --> 00:03:37.600
I also think, though, in relation to that, the last sentence that you read sort of answers the question,

00:03:37.840 --> 00:03:42.960
because what humans possess is the capacity for self-consciousness.

00:03:43.580 --> 00:03:49.980
And so in order for spirit to become conscious of itself, it needs human understanding to do that.

00:03:51.360 --> 00:03:53.980
So human understanding is this sort of vehicle.

00:03:54.180 --> 00:03:57.860
You clearly have – I mean, I think it's – the pages that we read this time,

00:03:57.920 --> 00:04:02.500
I think it's very hard not to have just a totally transcendental read of this.

00:04:04.040 --> 00:04:07.360
I mean, I think that there are places and ways that one can complicate that,

00:04:07.380 --> 00:04:11.400
so I'm not refuting whether it's Zizek or Malibu's readings.

00:04:11.800 --> 00:04:18.860
But in terms of this chunk, it does – spirit is this kind of quasi-independent force operating on its own.

00:04:18.860 --> 00:04:24.320
And it's kind of using individual – when we get to the question of the individual versus spirit,

00:04:24.860 --> 00:04:30.020
which he's dealing with there, the individual is just kind of a – what?

00:04:30.120 --> 00:04:35.860
Epiphenomena, you know, and clearly most individuals aren't along the way.

00:04:36.000 --> 00:04:40.140
I mean, most individuals are sort of retarded in their progress to spirit.

00:04:40.220 --> 00:04:45.280
Spirit has advanced past most – what we would call actual individuals.

00:04:45.980 --> 00:04:48.000
So, I mean, that's the short answer, I think.

00:04:48.000 --> 00:04:54.260
This chunk, I completely agree, is, like, probably the least appealing for me that we've gone through

00:04:54.260 --> 00:04:57.820
because it doesn't really vibe with the Malibu reading especially.

00:04:58.960 --> 00:05:05.060
Particularly all the stuff about, like, progress and cultural formation and the necessity of that

00:05:05.060 --> 00:05:11.840
and just the kind of clear, obvious, inescapable teleological language that's scattered throughout all this.

00:05:11.840 --> 00:05:20.280
Now, of course, my reading is he'll come to these – not synthesis, but complicating points throughout where it's like,

00:05:20.340 --> 00:05:26.640
oh, you could still attach to that throughout here, but you can't ignore the drive to transcendence,

00:05:26.960 --> 00:05:29.440
especially from 23 to 33 here.

00:05:29.840 --> 00:05:37.540
And, yeah, the little bit that you pointed out, I mean, he's really celebrating the power of the understanding here,

00:05:37.660 --> 00:05:44.380
which is just that basic scientific categorizing impulse where you just understand and appropriate the world.

00:05:44.520 --> 00:05:49.780
So, he's fully celebrating that here, that kind of totalizing appropriative force.

00:05:50.200 --> 00:05:54.740
Although he's going to complicate—I mean, he'll complicate that towards the end of the chunk, you know,

00:05:54.740 --> 00:05:56.760
where he says, look, it's not—that's not enough.

00:05:56.820 --> 00:06:02.560
In fact, you have to sort of defamiliarize, right, from the familiar functions of consciousness.

00:06:02.780 --> 00:06:07.360
But, nevertheless, it's still consciousness, whether it's at the level of fact or at the level of perception.

00:06:07.360 --> 00:06:13.700
It's still—human consciousness is the thing that is the vehicle for spirit's progress.

00:06:13.860 --> 00:06:17.460
Without human consciousness, spirit would have no play.

00:06:17.560 --> 00:06:18.560
So, that's what I mean.

00:06:18.620 --> 00:06:23.880
It's just—it's a pretty straightforward Enlightenment narrative that you get here.

00:06:23.940 --> 00:06:28.260
Yeah, well, I mean, it's the Phenomenology as well.

00:06:28.320 --> 00:06:31.040
I mean, it's a phenomenological account of the world.

00:06:31.140 --> 00:06:37.420
It's not claiming to be—or it's not trying to do what people like Spinoza are doing, right?

00:06:37.460 --> 00:06:39.880
I mean, it's not trying to be materialist in that sense.

00:06:39.880 --> 00:06:47.320
So, for Hegel, consciousness has to be schematized in this way for there to be, like, whatever,

00:06:47.440 --> 00:06:53.140
this kind of rigorous philosophy of the world, of how we interface with the world.

00:06:53.220 --> 00:06:59.280
I think for someone like Hegel and then particularly people that take him up, consciousness has to be primary,

00:06:59.620 --> 00:07:05.900
not because you elevate it because it's this amazing thing, but precisely because of what it lacks.

00:07:06.540 --> 00:07:09.340
You know, I didn't fully articulate that as well as I could.

00:07:09.340 --> 00:07:12.360
But I get why, like, you guys are hesitating.

00:07:12.500 --> 00:07:15.480
Like, why is the human centered here?

00:07:15.980 --> 00:07:22.440
But for the dialectic to work, just even to function at sort of a general capacity,

00:07:22.440 --> 00:07:24.980
it has to be centered around consciousness, doesn't it?

00:07:25.460 --> 00:07:27.700
I mean, the failures of consciousness.

00:07:28.080 --> 00:07:29.000
Contradiction, yeah.

00:07:29.160 --> 00:07:31.160
I mean, whether it's failure or success doesn't matter.

00:07:31.420 --> 00:07:32.100
Right, right, right.

00:07:32.100 --> 00:07:42.520
It requires, I mean, a logic of identity, the law of the excluded middle, like the whole apparatus of logic is necessary here.

00:07:42.580 --> 00:07:48.620
And look, I mean, I still think you can say the same things, which is that he goes further because it's always a process of development.

00:07:48.620 --> 00:07:55.220
It's never something that can be encapsulated in a proposition, that it's always a question of development.

00:07:55.340 --> 00:08:07.160
But that development does seem to be driven by this transcended force called spirit that I think it's not unfair to ask the question why humans are necessary,

00:08:07.500 --> 00:08:16.100
even though I do think that the answer is because they're the ones that are presumed to have the capacity for consciousness and hence self-consciousness.

00:08:16.100 --> 00:08:26.580
You know, they can shift the in to the for, you know, the in itself to the for itself, whereas no other entity, a living entity can do that.

00:08:31.100 --> 00:08:37.880
The two questions are related, but I kind of also want to highlight the important distinction as well.

00:08:37.880 --> 00:08:47.900
Like, the first question is, is why conscious, like, why begin from the premise that the all is one unified and unified consciousness, right?

00:08:47.920 --> 00:08:53.620
Or the becoming conscious of the one or of the whole, which we're going to call God, right?

00:08:53.680 --> 00:08:55.980
So, like, why begin from there?

00:08:56.180 --> 00:09:00.260
And, you know, this is actually, this one's more specifically related to a paragraph.

00:09:00.720 --> 00:09:11.520
I think it was 23, the very first one that we read, where he's talking about the God and the needing to add the predicate to the God.

00:09:11.620 --> 00:09:21.100
And it's like, you know, God is just a meaningless sound until you add something else to it that starts to give it shape and form.

00:09:21.100 --> 00:09:29.600
But then you obviously have to ask, like, why not just be like the ancients and start talking about, just drop the meaningless word and start talking about notions like being and the one.

00:09:29.680 --> 00:09:51.060
And his response is just like, well, obviously, because when you put the subjective, like, when you make these concepts like being and love and everything else, not pure abstract concepts, and you make them predicates of a subject, then it can be the sort of unfolding of self-realization.

00:09:51.060 --> 00:09:59.060
But that just seems incredibly tautological to me, is I don't understand why you need to start with the subject and self-reflection to begin with.

00:09:59.140 --> 00:10:08.820
Like, why is that to, lacking a better word, why is that the ontotheological starting point?

00:10:09.040 --> 00:10:10.060
That's one question.

00:10:10.440 --> 00:10:16.420
And then the other question is, like, let's presume that, you know, we come up with a satisfactory answer to that first one.

00:10:16.580 --> 00:10:21.100
And we're like, oh, yeah, obviously, you know, we have to start with subject and blah, blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

00:10:21.560 --> 00:10:24.540
Then it becomes, why do humans matter to that process?

00:10:24.940 --> 00:10:33.240
And I get what you're saying, John, that, well, humans just so happen to have understanding and thereby were the vehicle through which this process happens.

00:10:33.480 --> 00:10:56.500
But why would we assume that, given, I think you're right, given the way that humans are functionally epiphenomenon, and he's constantly sort of, like, differing between the knowledge that is the movement of absolute spirit and the process of development of individuals, which they don't seem to be the same thing at all to me.

00:10:56.720 --> 00:11:08.940
Like, given the fact that there is a difference between human understanding and understanding qua understanding, why would we ever presume that one is the vehicle for the other?

00:11:09.160 --> 00:11:20.300
Like, why does my becoming self-reflective of something in some way mirror or allow for a, like, God to become conscious of itself?

00:11:20.300 --> 00:11:26.060
And was, did God have zero self-consciousness before humans, you know, arrived on the scene?

00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:31.940
You know, like, that's the other thing, is how do humans happen to begin with?

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:41.320
And I don't want to make this too much of a natural history, but, like, is, for someone who's a thinker of movement and evolution, right, like, where do humans come from?

00:11:41.320 --> 00:11:49.680
But I think that is the, that's the almost just explicit theology here, which is, it's not that humans just happen to have consciousness.

00:11:50.280 --> 00:11:59.380
Humans are the beings granted consciousness as a way of apprehending and advancing God slash spirit, right?

00:11:59.480 --> 00:12:01.580
That, that's, that's what they're there for.

00:12:01.580 --> 00:12:12.140
So that you have that very, you know, 18th, 19th century theology, which is, like, human destiny is the fulfillment and realization of, of theological consciousness.

00:12:12.340 --> 00:12:13.600
Like, that's what it is.

00:12:14.680 --> 00:12:20.540
And so it's not an attribute that happens to fall to, to these animals as we think.

00:12:20.540 --> 00:12:33.940
But it's also, I mean, to provisionally answer your first question, Nathaniel, a little bit at least, I mean, the reason that subjectivity comes first here is, like you're saying, it could be attributed from God, but it's not a choice.

00:12:34.300 --> 00:12:40.040
It's a compulsion and a tendency for humans that is, whatever you want to call it, inescapable.

00:12:40.180 --> 00:12:48.320
So here on 24, he says, it's only as a science or as a system that knowing is actual and can be given an exposition.

00:12:48.980 --> 00:12:49.980
And you say, well, why?

00:12:50.340 --> 00:12:53.540
Why does science have to be a system for anything to be actual?

00:12:53.940 --> 00:12:55.840
Why do we have to systematize the world?

00:12:56.600 --> 00:12:59.140
Why is that the movement that Hegel's privileging here?

00:12:59.140 --> 00:13:03.860
And it's because you can't get out of that movement of systematization for him.

00:13:04.180 --> 00:13:16.180
So the kind of, the anti-philosophical orientation, whether you attribute that to Nietzsche to some extent, maybe Lacan, where they're trying to get outside of that, right?

00:13:16.220 --> 00:13:18.860
That impulse to systematize, that's the bad thing.

00:13:18.980 --> 00:13:19.560
To an extent.

00:13:20.080 --> 00:13:23.820
For Hegel, it's like, you don't get away from that.

00:13:24.000 --> 00:13:31.320
So at a very, at a structural level, the subject, subjectivity is an attempt to systematize.

00:13:31.540 --> 00:13:33.160
That I completely understand.

00:13:33.160 --> 00:13:39.420
And I understand, you know, that the very human drive, I think, you know, Nietzsche attends to this as well.

00:13:39.500 --> 00:13:49.520
It's like the drive to lie to oneself, to systematize and create equivalencies between things because it allows, it enables our survival, right?

00:13:49.560 --> 00:13:56.040
And then you could also say that, you know, no system is ever going to be able to carve up the world without remainder.

00:13:56.200 --> 00:14:00.820
So now you're going to be able to talk about failure as well, right?

00:14:00.880 --> 00:14:06.240
Or it's the movement to be able to talk about failure is much easier there than I think it normally is.

00:14:06.420 --> 00:14:07.820
But that's not the subject.

00:14:07.940 --> 00:14:24.360
I understand, you know, once you start with subjectivity, once you start with power relationships that render one being subject to another one and sort of like start categorizing and systematizing the world that creates that auto subjects as well.

00:14:24.520 --> 00:14:26.120
I understand that movement.

00:14:26.120 --> 00:14:31.920
I understand why, I don't understand why you have to start with subjects there, but I understand why subjectivity is unavoidable.

00:14:32.020 --> 00:14:41.360
But I'm talking about, when you're talking about absolute spirit, it sounds like you're talking about something ontologically prior to human subjectivity, right?

00:14:41.480 --> 00:14:52.360
Like God seems to, you know, humans, even if humans become the sort of designated vehicle through which, you know, God realizes himself, it doesn't have to be humans.

00:14:52.360 --> 00:14:54.660
And God can get along without humans just fine.

00:14:54.660 --> 00:15:03.000
My question is, why do we start with all that is in this theological principle, right?

00:15:03.400 --> 00:15:08.120
And I think maybe like, I mean, and obviously, you know, just, you could just say, well, it's theology, right?

00:15:08.220 --> 00:15:12.160
He was Lutheran, he, like, he has to begin with God, right?

00:15:12.180 --> 00:15:20.680
And this whole thing is actually really quite onto theological in which, and if that's the answer, then I'm curious more like how do the more interesting reads of Hegel,

00:15:20.680 --> 00:15:24.220
like Malibu and Zizek deal with that?

00:15:24.420 --> 00:15:28.520
Malibu has stuff on this, I know, just, I haven't read it, but I found the chunk.

00:15:28.580 --> 00:15:29.920
She definitely treats it.

00:15:30.400 --> 00:15:37.120
I mean, I would have to go back to them because this is something that I've sort of bracketed in my own dealing with Hegel so far,

00:15:37.220 --> 00:15:41.980
and even dealing with Zizek and Malibu, because it's, it's obviously a complicated question.

00:15:41.980 --> 00:15:49.520
And I don't think anybody has truly dealt with that in a satisfying way, at least from what I remember reading their text.

00:15:49.520 --> 00:15:58.840
You either get, you know, the kind of standard traditionalist reading of Hegel, which kind of just reifies some of those points and accepts them, right?

00:15:58.920 --> 00:16:02.220
Like even celebrates the God portion of Hegel.

00:16:02.380 --> 00:16:10.040
Or you get Malibu and Zizek who are almost singularly focused on contingency and how that unravels the God figure.

00:16:10.760 --> 00:16:11.440
So, I mean.

00:16:11.680 --> 00:16:14.080
Well, that's like the, you get an anthropological Hegel.

00:16:14.080 --> 00:16:14.560
Exactly.

00:16:14.660 --> 00:16:16.580
Rather than a theological Hegel.

00:16:16.580 --> 00:16:16.920
Exactly.

00:16:17.060 --> 00:16:24.900
And I clearly trend towards the, the anthropological one, just because it, you know, trends towards my.

00:16:24.900 --> 00:16:25.300
It's more interesting.

00:16:25.320 --> 00:16:25.960
Yeah, it's more interesting.

00:16:26.160 --> 00:16:28.140
It vibes with my sensibility more.

00:16:28.260 --> 00:16:30.060
But your question is completely viable.

00:16:30.180 --> 00:16:35.700
I mean, it's not really one that I've, like, reckoned with at a, at a serious level yet.

00:16:35.820 --> 00:16:38.280
I've kind of just been like, well, there is God.

00:16:38.400 --> 00:16:39.540
I don't really like that.

00:16:40.540 --> 00:16:40.780
You know.

00:16:44.660 --> 00:16:49.260
Well, I mean, I think it would be easy and productive to bracket a lot of it, right?

00:16:49.320 --> 00:16:51.780
Because I, you know, I've said this a few times.

00:16:51.860 --> 00:16:58.680
I think a lot of this, especially that second layer of sort of like progressive, you know, the progressivity of the movement of spirit.

00:16:58.940 --> 00:17:07.800
And it's sort of like overarching telos that isn't self-posited, but that, well, it's self-posited as just sort of the being of God, right?

00:17:07.800 --> 00:17:11.120
Like, I think so much of that could be easily lapped off the top.

00:17:11.200 --> 00:17:15.280
And if you do that, then it's like all this other stuff is interesting, right?

00:17:15.340 --> 00:17:19.840
All the other stuff becomes much more interesting if you are just able to subtract God from it.

00:17:19.900 --> 00:17:21.200
I think that you can do it.

00:17:21.320 --> 00:17:23.100
I think that you can link them.

00:17:23.100 --> 00:17:52.100
Like, I don't think I've seen an indication that there is spirit other than, like, removed from human consciousness, which is to say, I don't get a sense here so far that there was first spirit and then, you know, and then, because the necessity of human consciousness to progress.

00:17:52.100 --> 00:17:57.660
The necessity of spirit to progress is the necessity of spirit to progress.

00:17:57.660 --> 00:18:00.640
And now, that doesn't mean that every individual human does it.

00:18:00.700 --> 00:18:02.720
In fact, most of them don't, right?

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:06.500
Like, most of them are the sort of dead ends along the path.

00:18:06.720 --> 00:18:14.300
But there are some, you know, that are pushing thinking and understanding further.

00:18:14.480 --> 00:18:16.140
And that is the evolution.

00:18:16.780 --> 00:18:19.060
That's what spirit wants, right?

00:18:19.140 --> 00:18:19.820
That's what drives.

00:18:19.920 --> 00:18:25.040
And spirit, in this sense, as that which animates subjectivity itself, right?

00:18:25.080 --> 00:18:27.140
It's not, it's certainly not external.

00:18:27.420 --> 00:18:29.640
I mean, even if it's transcendent, it's not external.

00:18:31.040 --> 00:18:35.180
It is the animating force of subjectivity.

00:18:36.000 --> 00:18:40.220
And I don't think there's anything to, any reason to believe it's anything other than that.

00:18:40.320 --> 00:18:40.660
Right.

00:18:41.080 --> 00:18:42.500
Well, it can't be totally external.

00:18:42.720 --> 00:18:46.520
I mean, we've talked about the movement of internalization and that dialectic.

00:18:46.740 --> 00:18:50.960
But what you just said makes me think he's much closer to Spinoza.

00:18:50.960 --> 00:18:57.140
Maybe even in an explicit way, he's drawing from Spinoza there, where God is completely immanent, right?

00:18:57.380 --> 00:19:02.300
To the material, like, manifestation of human being, of subjectivity.

00:19:02.660 --> 00:19:04.720
God is there at an immanent level.

00:19:04.880 --> 00:19:07.240
I mean, what you just said sort of sounded like that.

00:19:07.580 --> 00:19:08.120
You know what I mean?

00:19:08.160 --> 00:19:12.180
It's like, it's not, he's not above in heaven directing our movement.

00:19:13.040 --> 00:19:14.780
It's definitely not, it's not that.

00:19:14.900 --> 00:19:16.380
I don't, I don't think it is that.

00:19:16.380 --> 00:19:23.620
I think it is, I don't, I still don't, I don't think it's Spinoza insofar as spirit wants something, right?

00:19:23.680 --> 00:19:32.400
Like, spirit is, is directed, it is, it wants its own overcoming and its own becoming self-conscious of its moments.

00:19:32.960 --> 00:19:35.440
And the problem, of course, is for the individuals.

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:43.020
But the individuals are completely necessary components to, to spirit's self, you know, self-realization.

00:19:43.340 --> 00:19:50.420
So our goal, our purpose in life is to realize spirit's, you know, absoluteness.

00:19:51.040 --> 00:19:51.680
We're always going to fail to do that.

00:19:51.680 --> 00:19:53.940
We're always going to fail to do that.

00:19:54.160 --> 00:19:58.820
I mean, we're like, any particular individual will of necessity fail to do that.

00:19:59.120 --> 00:20:04.100
But humanity as a whole won't fail to do that because that's what its purpose is.

00:20:04.460 --> 00:20:15.660
So that makes it much more interesting because you could, you could make that, if you wanted to go theological, then you would have to, you would probably say something more like, the human is imminent to God.

00:20:15.660 --> 00:20:23.500
Like, is the sort of, you know, like, really the human is nothing other than a moment of the self alienation of God.

00:20:23.640 --> 00:20:25.140
I was, no, you're quite right.

00:20:25.180 --> 00:20:31.940
I was thinking that on the section on analysis where he talks about, you know, cutting up the principle into smaller parts, right?

00:20:32.020 --> 00:20:34.500
I was like, you could imagine a story that goes like this.

00:20:34.900 --> 00:20:40.260
First, there is spirit and spirit analyzes itself, meaning it cuts itself up into its moments.

00:20:40.380 --> 00:20:42.480
And one of them is called humans, right?

00:20:42.980 --> 00:20:47.420
One of those sort of analytic moments that then has an engine of its own, right?

00:20:47.460 --> 00:20:52.280
Like, I mean, you could tell the story if you wanted to have spirit sort of pre-exist.

00:20:53.220 --> 00:21:19.320
So you could run it that way, or if you wanted to go the more anthropological way, is you could say that human consciousness, human capacity to think and understanding sort of emerges from human activity and then, and it posits its own telos that, you know, is this what we call the capacity of human thinking?

00:21:19.320 --> 00:21:27.640
Which, you know, that would be, you know, one, that could be a contingent development within a much wider array of happening.

00:21:28.860 --> 00:21:37.340
Two, it would explain why there are so many dead ends, because some kinds of thinking are going to kind of propel self-consciousness and other ones aren't.

00:21:37.480 --> 00:21:47.100
And it would also explain why there are subjects, because thinking is predicated on the emergence of power relations that make one thing subject to another.

00:21:47.940 --> 00:21:48.900
Irresolvable relations.

00:21:49.320 --> 00:21:49.520
Right.

00:21:49.580 --> 00:21:54.580
That's what drives the movement of systematization.

00:21:54.580 --> 00:22:11.120
Like, in Zizek's language, you could probably say that, like, the function of God is a crack in the edifice of subjectivity, where the inability to appropriate creates that compulsion.

00:22:11.360 --> 00:22:23.120
It's that constant folding process, where the inconsistencies of conceptuality, of thinking, leads, that's the drive, right, to conceptualize.

00:22:23.620 --> 00:22:24.460
And it's...

00:22:24.460 --> 00:22:29.620
So God, both as sort of the ineffable and the desire.

00:22:30.500 --> 00:22:32.300
God is pure desire and ineffability.

00:22:34.620 --> 00:22:40.820
So, I mean, the question we're asking here is, what starts the negative going?

00:22:41.500 --> 00:22:48.880
And is it some anthropological component, or is it some transcendent theological component?

00:22:49.760 --> 00:22:54.980
Or is it, of course, you know, a synthesis of the two?

00:22:55.080 --> 00:22:57.260
Or is it some sort of merger, you know?

00:22:57.420 --> 00:23:02.340
And I do, I mean, it is my sense, like, I still think it's clearly transcendent.

00:23:02.940 --> 00:23:04.540
But I don't think it's external.

00:23:05.220 --> 00:23:15.340
You know, it is irreducible to the particular individuals, you know, but it is not greater than that either.

00:23:15.340 --> 00:23:18.820
Or at least there's no reason to believe that there is some sort of, like, more...

00:23:18.820 --> 00:23:23.000
So, like, spirit is not more advanced than human consciousness, for instance.

00:23:23.440 --> 00:23:28.800
But human consciousness here means the totality of the movement of all human consciousness.

00:23:28.940 --> 00:23:31.240
It doesn't mean my consciousness, your consciousness, right?

00:23:31.360 --> 00:23:39.400
Like, so, again, it actually is very predicated on a fairly discrete sense of individuality that's only linked through the theological.

00:23:39.980 --> 00:23:45.220
That's, to me, where the Nietzschean-Deleuzian lineage is way more interesting in that regard.

00:23:45.220 --> 00:23:56.240
Because if there's a transcendence of the virtual, it's a very different sense of connection among consciousness than, like, you know, relatively static.

00:23:56.240 --> 00:24:03.500
I mean, they're not static, obviously, but relatively discreet and homogenous individuals.

00:24:04.060 --> 00:24:05.680
Yeah, but it does make it...

00:24:05.680 --> 00:24:09.960
I mean, one, it makes that sort of appropriation monster a little bit less.

00:24:09.980 --> 00:24:13.680
It's less scary because it localizes this phenomenon.

00:24:14.100 --> 00:24:26.340
Because, I mean, you know, the way that he writes and the way that I've been imagining this as the sort of, like, universalizing at an ontological level, like, all is this, right?

00:24:26.740 --> 00:24:38.320
And running through this much more anthropological lens or this line allows this little mini appropriation monster, which isn't mini.

00:24:38.440 --> 00:24:39.660
I mean, it's all of human consciousness.

00:24:40.060 --> 00:24:52.740
But in the grand scheme of things, it's pretty tiny to sort of, like, churn out and only relate to otherness through, you know, appropriation and alienation.

00:24:53.680 --> 00:24:54.980
You don't start with, I agree with you.

00:24:55.040 --> 00:24:55.260
Right.

00:24:55.340 --> 00:24:57.280
But then you don't, but then you don't get a start.

00:24:57.340 --> 00:25:04.080
Like, when you say starting with the whole isn't, this is just, like, not Spinoza, right?

00:25:04.140 --> 00:25:04.880
This is not Spinoza.

00:25:04.960 --> 00:25:05.780
This is not Deleuze.

00:25:05.780 --> 00:25:09.320
You have to start with something that thinks of itself as a whole.

00:25:09.660 --> 00:25:11.000
Yeah, that is human consciousness.

00:25:11.260 --> 00:25:16.340
That really is within this much larger heterogeneous matrix, right?

00:25:16.460 --> 00:25:16.640
Yeah.

00:25:16.820 --> 00:25:30.300
Well, there's where, I mean, to sort out the way I've been sorting it out in my head is, like, that's where it's useful to think of Hegel as symptomatic of his own, of the dialectic, rather than being, like, the master of it.

00:25:31.460 --> 00:25:35.760
Because, you guys are right, the totalizing impulses runs all throughout.

00:25:36.020 --> 00:25:39.500
The drive towards transcendence is there.

00:25:40.160 --> 00:26:00.440
But thinking of him as symptomatic of that movement, rather than being on top of it, gives me a little better, right, I don't know, just that kind of diagnostic reading of Hegel, rather than just, like, putting him up as the one who figured out the way the world works, to me is a little more useful.

00:26:00.440 --> 00:26:10.340
Well, yeah, I mean, and I get it from, I mean, again, from an anthropological standpoint, but I'm always going to say, and I think the same thing about psychoanalysis, it's just inevitably going to remain an idealist philosophy.

00:26:10.480 --> 00:26:11.120
It can't not.

00:26:11.620 --> 00:26:22.280
You know, there's just no way for it to really take materiality, a constitutive element, or to say something like, you know, the Nietzsche quote from last time, which is the consciousness hasn't caught up to the body.

00:26:22.280 --> 00:26:30.600
Like, that's just an impossible, impossible thought for this, you know, something that starts with consciousness as the engine.

00:26:30.760 --> 00:26:32.300
It just can't ever get there.

00:26:32.420 --> 00:26:35.940
Because materiality is always going to be, what's the thing that enables consciousness?

00:26:36.040 --> 00:26:40.320
It's like, I mean, you know, we have that today in the life sciences.

00:26:40.520 --> 00:26:44.900
It's like, what are the material configurations that allow for the emergence of consciousness?

00:26:45.140 --> 00:26:50.960
In other words, materiality is thought as the substrate condition of possibility for this higher thing.

00:26:51.180 --> 00:26:53.320
It's never the other way around, right?

00:26:53.460 --> 00:26:58.640
Like, and it's never consciousness simply as an epiphenomena of materiality, right?

00:26:58.680 --> 00:27:02.820
It's always like a kind of kilos of materiality.

00:27:03.240 --> 00:27:11.420
But I think there's much, much better reason, at least to me, to believe that consciousness is literally one attribute among others, you know?

00:27:11.640 --> 00:27:20.980
And, I mean, that's where the Nietzsche truth and lies, the beginning of the truth and lies essay of, like, man, we take this knowledge thing so fucking seriously as if it's the pinnacle of all things.

00:27:21.080 --> 00:27:25.620
But it's just a survival mechanism for a particular kind of animal, you know?

00:27:25.620 --> 00:27:32.580
And so we don't ask, you wouldn't ask the question of, like, what is the origin of claws, right?

00:27:32.660 --> 00:27:35.320
Like, because claws or fangs or, you know what I mean?

00:27:35.400 --> 00:27:38.660
Like, because we just don't see that as a pinnacle.

00:27:38.820 --> 00:27:42.060
But consciousness, what are the material conditions that enable consciousness?

00:27:42.060 --> 00:27:51.060
We ask questions like that even today all the time, you know, that the whole emergent consciousness, Maturana and Varela thing is all about that.

00:27:51.440 --> 00:27:54.060
And that's the edgy, cool stuff, you know?

00:27:54.180 --> 00:28:00.600
But it still thinks materiality is the condition of possibility for this kind of higher thing.

00:28:00.860 --> 00:28:02.260
That's basically Barad.

00:28:02.500 --> 00:28:06.540
I mean, she wouldn't flat out say that, but that is kind of the movement of that system.

00:28:07.540 --> 00:28:08.260
Yeah, I don't know.

00:28:08.320 --> 00:28:11.060
I just think flattening it, like, you're right.

00:28:11.140 --> 00:28:16.920
You shouldn't raise it up as this, like, the best thing about us or about the world.

00:28:17.080 --> 00:28:20.860
But flattening it out doesn't, is not useful for me either.

00:28:21.040 --> 00:28:22.060
Like, where it's just everything.

00:28:22.060 --> 00:28:23.480
That's what we mean by flattening, though.

00:28:23.620 --> 00:28:25.260
I mean, it doesn't mean homogenizing.

00:28:25.260 --> 00:28:26.980
Yeah, you can't think of it as reducing.

00:28:26.980 --> 00:28:31.280
But where it's all in the same ontological plane, like, just a force among forces.

00:28:31.580 --> 00:28:31.820
Right.

00:28:31.940 --> 00:28:34.300
I mean, I get, I do get the appeal of that.

00:28:34.420 --> 00:28:38.800
I just, for, at least for my project, it's like, that's almost unthinkable.

00:28:38.940 --> 00:28:44.140
Just because of, like, it's, okay, maybe we'll put consciousness below everything else.

00:28:44.420 --> 00:28:45.760
I still need it somewhere.

00:28:46.280 --> 00:28:46.840
You know what I mean?

00:28:46.840 --> 00:28:49.320
Like, I need to put it somewhere rather than...

00:28:49.320 --> 00:28:53.600
If you have a flat plane, then it's to the left or to the right, right?

00:28:53.620 --> 00:28:59.240
It's not above or below, but it attaches, it does this very unique kind of thing.

00:28:59.420 --> 00:29:02.960
And it attaches to these things and doesn't particularly attach well to these other things.

00:29:03.040 --> 00:29:06.040
But its particular attachments do really unique things.

00:29:06.040 --> 00:29:11.420
So it would be never to reduce, like, consciousness or not claws, right?

00:29:11.420 --> 00:29:11.640
Yeah, of course.

00:29:11.640 --> 00:29:12.960
They do very different things.

00:29:13.060 --> 00:29:16.540
I mean, if you generalize to a certain point, like, yeah, they're both survival mechanisms.

00:29:16.840 --> 00:29:22.940
But what they enable bodies to do and the kinds of life that they allow for are very, very different.

00:29:27.480 --> 00:29:37.340
I think it's crucial to say, when putting something on a flat plane is not, even though it's often taken, as you just did, it's often taken as a homogenizing impulse.

00:29:37.340 --> 00:29:43.260
To me, it is the quintessential differentiating impulse, is to say, these things are different.

00:29:44.000 --> 00:29:45.980
That's what putting them on a flat plane does.

00:29:46.120 --> 00:29:52.060
Whereas the hierarchical version of it, what that does is it creates two kind of fundamentally different planes.

00:29:52.160 --> 00:29:56.860
And there's no way of seeing those two planes as not inferior or superior versions of one another.

00:29:57.280 --> 00:30:00.440
That putting it on a flat plane is the way of attending to difference.

00:30:00.540 --> 00:30:01.720
It is not the erasure.

00:30:02.380 --> 00:30:10.020
And in all fairness, I know plenty of people, for instance, an equivalent sort of move in the field of rhetoric is the saying of everything is rhetoric.

00:30:11.240 --> 00:30:22.480
You know, everything is rhetoric or everything is rhetorical, however it's often said, is a way of oftentimes of homogenizing all things and to say, well, they're basically the same kind of thing.

00:30:22.480 --> 00:30:32.880
Whereas to me, and I've written about this too and said, like, look, it's absolutely crucial that the claim that everything is rhetorical be the starting point of an inquiry, not the end point.

00:30:33.140 --> 00:30:39.800
The proposition that says, discipline X, that just so happens to be my discipline, everything is that thing, right?

00:30:39.900 --> 00:30:40.900
Everything is economics.

00:30:41.100 --> 00:30:41.980
Everything is political.

00:30:42.180 --> 00:30:43.100
Everything is rhetorical.

00:30:43.220 --> 00:30:43.800
Everything is.

00:30:44.440 --> 00:30:47.760
And, you know, I imagine that you can have these same kinds of arguments.

00:30:47.880 --> 00:30:52.360
I don't know the specifics of them, but that we've had about, you know, big and small tent rhetoric.

00:30:52.820 --> 00:30:58.780
But, like, I don't think it's all that difficult to see them as non-mutually exclusive.

00:30:58.920 --> 00:31:04.260
In other words, economics is rhetorical and rhetoric is economical, right?

00:31:04.260 --> 00:31:32.500
And what that—all that really does is allows you to rethink—you get to remake rhetoric in interesting ways by attending to certain economic forces, right, that you would say if you're going to do it, as you say, John, to figure out the differentiations, would remake the way that we think of rhetoric and also, in fact, remake the way that we think of economics if you do it really thoughtfully.

00:31:32.500 --> 00:31:48.220
I do think that is the premise behind something into which I totally buy at this stage of my thinking is the move towards a kind of monism, you know, in its various incarnations.

00:31:48.220 --> 00:32:02.680
But the move, the reason for going to the univocity of being, let's say, Duns Scotus, you know, the move for that, those sort of monist thinkings is precisely because that's the only way of differentiating among things.

00:32:02.940 --> 00:32:26.080
That if you have a sense of a dualism, you know, transcendence, eminence, I mean, all of our conceptual coordinates, what that—it can't but create a hierarchy such that each thing is seen as an inferior, superior version of the—you know, like—so, you know, enter deconstruction and all of the moves that it makes.

00:32:26.080 --> 00:32:32.040
So, for Derrida, the monism is different, iteration, depends on the thing that you're reading.

00:32:32.500 --> 00:32:42.900
But it's all monistic and that's the impetus behind it is to show the differentiating force of beginning with a monist thinking.

00:32:43.080 --> 00:32:52.460
But you could read Hegel that way too if you wanted to, you know, like spirit—like we were just saying, I mean, if God is not in the sky, then he's with us all the time.

00:32:52.540 --> 00:32:54.200
I mean, that is a version of monism.

00:32:54.700 --> 00:32:58.080
It's—you self—you self-differentiate.

00:32:58.460 --> 00:33:00.320
But it depends on how—it depends on how he's with us though.

00:33:00.460 --> 00:33:03.040
I mean, that's where it depends.

00:33:03.220 --> 00:33:04.720
Yeah, I mean, you certainly can.

00:33:04.780 --> 00:33:07.220
And I don't get the sense that it's a God in the sky.

00:33:07.220 --> 00:33:11.020
I do get a sense that it's this, you know, interior, innervating force.

00:33:11.600 --> 00:33:26.100
Nevertheless, I also do still get the sense that spirit somehow—so, for instance, I mean, this is a response to your earlier point about not seeing Hegel as the pinnacle of the thing.

00:33:26.740 --> 00:33:32.600
But given the thinking here, I see why Hegel thinks he's the pinnacle of the thing.

00:33:33.100 --> 00:33:34.840
It makes total sense, right?

00:33:34.840 --> 00:33:44.140
If in particular instances, human individuals become more self-conscious than other humans, that's the development of spirit.

00:33:44.280 --> 00:33:45.760
That's the advancement of spirit.

00:33:46.100 --> 00:33:49.960
And those are the sort of people who are doing the yeoman's work of spirit.

00:33:50.300 --> 00:34:04.820
So, in that sense, spirit is still transcendent because— not because it's separate from and up in some God heaven, but because it wants something that's different from individual consciousness, individual consciousness, right?

00:34:04.860 --> 00:34:08.680
Like, that there is a sense of a telos of spirit to progress.

00:34:09.560 --> 00:34:14.820
And insofar as that's the case, then it still maintains a kind of transcendence.

00:34:14.880 --> 00:34:21.320
Not the transcendence of the God up in the sky, but a kind of transcendence in relation to its particular moments.

00:34:21.320 --> 00:34:27.080
So, let's think that through, like, Duchesne and Deleuzian appropriation for a moment.

00:34:27.760 --> 00:34:36.080
And, you know, like, a thing doesn't reveal what it is until it's been taken or takes something else.

00:34:36.500 --> 00:34:46.380
And so, you know, like, imagine force A appropriating force B with a purpose, like, with the desire of expressing itself through that other thing.

00:34:46.380 --> 00:34:49.480
So, imagine this thing that we're going to call consciousness.

00:34:49.760 --> 00:34:52.260
Let's, you know, not, like, call it just human consciousness.

00:34:52.520 --> 00:34:57.240
Let's call some kind of will toward thinking or will of analysis or whatever else.

00:34:57.440 --> 00:35:04.140
And it takes hold of the human body or the human brain or whatever else it is and expresses itself through it.

00:35:04.720 --> 00:35:12.440
And, I mean, and now we have to subtract some kind of transcendental unity from it that is going to arrive at a predetermined place.

00:35:12.660 --> 00:35:25.860
Unless if you want to say that, like, you know, the kinds of conditions of development are in some ways contained within the particular intersection between the human and consciousness that takes over it.

00:35:26.640 --> 00:35:31.220
And you're going to have to, like, this is where consciousness is really going to have to be weird here.

00:35:31.220 --> 00:35:35.940
Because it's going to be hard to talk about consciousness independent of a thing, like consciousness, pure consciousness.

00:35:36.400 --> 00:35:38.420
You know, I don't know how to describe that just as a force.

00:35:39.100 --> 00:35:47.440
That's a way of thinking hierarchical relationships or transcendent relationships on a flat plane.

00:35:47.440 --> 00:35:50.140
Where it's, like, on a flat plane, two things encounter.

00:35:50.400 --> 00:35:57.420
One takes over the other, creates a hierarchical relationship that now is going to create a particular line of flight.

00:35:57.820 --> 00:36:06.140
That you could almost even say that given, you know, the velocity and direction and weight of the intersection.

00:36:06.880 --> 00:36:08.720
If you called that, it's telos.

00:36:09.000 --> 00:36:12.340
Well, why not, yeah, you're, I mean, why not performative hierarchies?

00:36:12.680 --> 00:36:14.160
Doesn't that kind of solve the issue?

00:36:14.480 --> 00:36:15.400
I mean, it does for me.

00:36:15.460 --> 00:36:21.160
Like, why do we have to get rid of the terms and the oppositions, the binaries?

00:36:21.640 --> 00:36:25.140
I'm not, this is not directed at Deleuze or Nietzsche or you guys.

00:36:25.220 --> 00:36:32.480
But the, I would say there's, like, a version that's one step lagging behind that, that kind of controls a lot of thinking.

00:36:32.860 --> 00:36:33.280
The Barat.

00:36:33.380 --> 00:36:35.300
The Barad is the perfect example of this.

00:36:35.300 --> 00:36:50.960
Or other kind of versions of ecological thinking, empiricist thinking, where the desire is to flatten oppositions and have materiality, ecology, be the kind of driving, vibrant force.

00:36:51.460 --> 00:36:55.420
And that, that's what ends up getting privileged at the expense of whatever.

00:36:55.580 --> 00:37:09.420
So, to me, the, the flattening of the opposition in Barad, not in Deleuze or whatever, that's just as naive as, like, well, not, it's potentially just as naive as, like, a full-throated investment in the subject-object opposition.

00:37:15.420 --> 00:37:18.820
I don't think materialism solves the problem, right?

00:37:18.900 --> 00:37:21.260
Like, I think materialism, I mean, I think that's what you're saying.

00:37:21.340 --> 00:37:26.260
Like, materialism introduces its, its own difficulties.

00:37:26.620 --> 00:37:36.000
And what materialism has to seek to do or has to figure out how to do is to think itself in a non-reductive sense of materiality.

00:37:36.540 --> 00:37:42.480
And, and that's, so I, I see that impulse in Barad, but I also, I mean, I agree with you.

00:37:42.540 --> 00:37:51.480
I see another kind of impulse in, maybe in Barad, but certainly in the eco folks that want to say, well, materiality is the, it's the baseline, right?

00:37:51.480 --> 00:38:07.720
And, and so, and I'm equally as averse to those, to those things, because those are just as, I mean, materiality as your monism, you know, as the sort of baseline thing, it can be just as reductive as idealism is.

00:38:08.260 --> 00:38:13.840
Because it then becomes, I mean, the argument would be something like, that's what the sciences are, right?

00:38:14.440 --> 00:38:18.400
The sciences are a monism of reductive materiality.

00:38:19.020 --> 00:38:23.620
Everything is explainable by physical chemical responses.

00:38:24.220 --> 00:38:31.200
So that, to me, that's just the flip side of saying everything is explainable as consciousness reflecting upon itself, right?

00:38:31.320 --> 00:38:37.300
But both of those, I mean, the point would be neither one of the positions buys you out in that regard.

00:38:37.420 --> 00:38:49.000
So that's where, why monism or the thinking of monism is difficult, you know, if it weren't, I mean, you know, so, so there's the ways in which, and it's not even that, you know, dualisms are bad.

00:38:49.000 --> 00:39:05.460
Or are, they are, I mean, I think of it in the, in the Thousand Plateaus terminology is that dualisms are the entirely necessary components that are constantly being rearranged to induce different kinds of monist multiplicities, you know?

00:39:05.460 --> 00:39:23.700
And so that's where, from this perspective, you would read someone like Hegel as a symptom of, of that kind of impulse towards multiplicity that's being canalized through, through the dualisms and the contradictions and the appropriate, and the appropriation machine.

00:39:23.860 --> 00:39:27.660
Because I think that if you say what you said, the performative, could you have the performative things?

00:39:27.980 --> 00:39:28.600
Yeah, you could.

00:39:28.740 --> 00:39:34.840
And then it becomes, as I think it always is, an ethical question, which is, what are the dangers of doing it that way?

00:39:35.140 --> 00:39:36.700
And they're big, right?

00:39:36.760 --> 00:39:39.480
They are, let's feed the appropriation machine.

00:39:39.840 --> 00:39:51.940
Right, so I mean, I think that's why, you know, I think some of the worry about flattening things out is that you get rid of a lot of the vitality because you get rid of oppositions, you get rid of dualities, you get rid of hierarchies.

00:39:51.940 --> 00:40:02.500
And I think that that's precisely why Deleuze turns to the flat ontology because he thinks that that's the only place where these kinds of things—

00:40:02.500 --> 00:40:05.160
You can have aggression without resentment.

00:40:05.160 --> 00:40:09.480
Yeah, where, like, dualities actually can do their work, right?

00:40:09.580 --> 00:40:22.820
Because when duality gets posited as a sort of difference in kind, that there is a kind of a natural relationship between the two that stands outside of the flat plane.

00:40:22.940 --> 00:40:25.760
They're on different planes—they are on different planes from each other.

00:40:26.100 --> 00:40:28.060
Then that becomes very static.

00:40:28.220 --> 00:40:33.800
Or if you want to take it from the self-conscious level, like, you create the hierarchy so that they can be then sublated.

00:40:33.800 --> 00:40:52.180
But if they—but if this happens on a flat plane, then there's no—like, dualities are much more interestingly relative, meaning that, like, anything can become in a dual relationship with anything else, right?

00:40:52.620 --> 00:41:00.040
You know, not even just that, well, it could have been the case—like, you know, if you—I'm thinking of Nietzsche on gender, right?

00:41:00.040 --> 00:41:14.400
And, you know, in some ways you could say that, you know, this thing that becomes what we call man becomes what we call man by taking and appropriating what we come to call woman, which now creates a line of flight for both of them to develop, right?

00:41:14.800 --> 00:41:23.360
And to strike to talk about the contingency of that, we could say it very well could have been the case that woman takes man as its object.

00:41:23.500 --> 00:41:28.040
And we have a whole different set of binaries and values that spin out of that.

00:41:28.520 --> 00:41:35.880
But, like, if you're going to take the multiplicity seriously, it doesn't have to be man or woman, right?

00:41:35.960 --> 00:41:42.520
Like, those terms only even come into effect because of a particular relationship.

00:41:42.600 --> 00:41:48.120
If that relationship were different, we would have just a completely different topology, right?

00:41:48.160 --> 00:42:00.160
Like, there's nothing necessary about man and woman being related to each other other than the fact that, contingently speaking, they were and genesis these terms, man, woman, and the whole value system that spins out of them.

00:42:00.160 --> 00:42:06.260
Yeah, I mean, in that case, dualism is just a particular configuration of multiplicity that human consciousness uses.

00:42:06.880 --> 00:42:08.160
So Hegel is a symptom.

00:42:08.740 --> 00:42:09.840
I should have just said that.

00:42:10.060 --> 00:42:20.400
But I know, but I mean, and your example is a particularly good one insofar as we're now living in a historical moment in which that particular binary, you know, you still have, you know, non-binary.

00:42:20.620 --> 00:42:24.900
You're starting to have these things appear on, you know, official forms and whatnot.

00:42:25.080 --> 00:42:31.600
And so it's the beginning and the backlash reaction against it is like, well, that's just fucking insanity.

00:42:31.800 --> 00:42:36.000
Everything's going to go to shit if you can't distinguish between men and women.

00:42:36.700 --> 00:42:51.020
And, but, but it's a symptom of a commitment to, we must have a dualist binary starting point as opposed to saying, no, we don't have, I mean, for humans, we have had to.

00:42:51.140 --> 00:42:59.200
And, but again, for humans and for human consciousness, that's just a particular way in which multiplicity has, has played itself out.

00:43:04.340 --> 00:43:17.140
The stringency of that heteronormativity, which may have been even more pressing or intense, like, you know, a couple of decades ago, that gave way for, I mean, why?

00:43:17.220 --> 00:43:22.920
Maybe because of its intensity, not because of like any kind of intention or choice.

00:43:23.040 --> 00:43:31.040
Like, that's why, I mean, not to, I don't, but like, you don't have to be, right, you don't have, but you don't have to be anti-Oedipus.

00:43:31.460 --> 00:43:33.620
I mean, Oedipus will dissolve on his own.

00:43:33.700 --> 00:43:34.920
He kind of already, you know what I mean?

00:43:34.960 --> 00:43:37.800
It's, it's doing that in today's culture.

00:43:38.080 --> 00:43:39.320
Well, or, well, or it won't.

00:43:39.400 --> 00:43:42.040
That's where I said, that's where it becomes an ethical question, right?

00:43:42.060 --> 00:43:43.900
Like, I mean, maybe it will, maybe it won't.

00:43:43.980 --> 00:43:44.740
I mean, who knows?

00:43:44.840 --> 00:43:47.340
But I mean, it is a question of how do you live, right?

00:43:47.340 --> 00:43:52.680
So given that, that sort of dualist paradigm, I mean, I agree with you.

00:43:52.720 --> 00:44:00.320
It's certainly not a choice and nor is it an obligation or a responsibility, but neither is it nothing, you know?

00:44:00.400 --> 00:44:04.340
So it's not irrelevant that a whole bunch of people say, you know what?

00:44:04.360 --> 00:44:05.400
I'm fucking non-binary.

00:44:05.620 --> 00:44:15.120
Like that, that produces an alteration in the thinking of the, or not just the thinking, the experience, you know, even, even broader of moving around.

00:44:15.120 --> 00:44:32.220
Well, and not, not to get all libertarian on us either, but like, you know, the, the, the fucking, like, you know, obviously increased progress and the proliferation of these various identity groups, sexual orientations, like that's produced a lot of good things.

00:44:32.220 --> 00:44:35.640
And it's made people literally safer in the world.

00:44:36.140 --> 00:44:38.820
So those are like clear, practical, good results.

00:44:38.820 --> 00:44:50.300
But you can see sort of obviously the way that all of these micro identities get codified into camps and it just becomes another version of, it's the biopower dynamic for Foucault.

00:44:50.500 --> 00:44:51.520
It's like, right.

00:44:51.880 --> 00:44:52.360
Yeah.

00:44:52.540 --> 00:44:57.100
So it's like, I mean, it's clearly not all good or bad or you can't frame in those terms.

00:44:57.100 --> 00:44:57.580
It never is.

00:44:57.680 --> 00:45:04.320
It's never, it's never like, I mean, I think Butler on the transgender question is really, is really good on this.

00:45:04.320 --> 00:45:08.740
Which is, look, you know, we have problems with the normalizing function of medicalization.

00:45:08.920 --> 00:45:14.000
And at the same time, that's how someone can get the insurance money to get the surgery that will save their life.

00:45:14.400 --> 00:45:15.580
So what do you do?

00:45:15.660 --> 00:45:15.840
Right.

00:45:15.960 --> 00:45:21.360
Like, and so there isn't, there isn't a good choice and there isn't a, and there isn't a bad choice.

00:45:21.500 --> 00:45:34.460
And I don't think that's the, I don't think it's, I mean, I don't think certainly here, I mean, actually here there's more moralism, you know, there's more of a moralism towards increasing self-consciousness than you're going to find in Nietzsche or Deleuze.

00:45:34.620 --> 00:45:52.440
You know, and so that's where, to me, interestingly enough, given your orientation, it would seem like, like, the non-moralizing positions where the, it's not non-moralizing, but the sort of rigorous attempts to problematize moralism, that ain't this.

00:45:52.600 --> 00:45:53.880
You know, this seems to be.

00:45:54.100 --> 00:45:56.320
Here's like, I think I've hit on this several times.

00:45:56.440 --> 00:46:09.040
It's, it's the, right, you're saying, like, well, we'll read Hegel as being symptomatic, and that's the key for me, is that everyone, to a certain extent, is symptomatic and has their own implicit moralisms.

00:46:09.300 --> 00:46:16.180
It's when someone like Barad claims not to be professing a moralism, where it's like, Hegel's clearly doing that.

00:46:16.480 --> 00:46:18.720
I mean, he's up front, I mean, this is what's good.

00:46:18.720 --> 00:46:26.420
The self-consciousness, we need to fucking keep marching forward to, like, that's not something I would, like, just endorse.

00:46:26.740 --> 00:46:35.120
Uncritically, it's, that's the sinister part of Hegel that I'm trying to wring out of other people, that they don't see that, that impulse in themselves.

00:46:35.540 --> 00:46:52.520
And I'm not, I, I think Deleuze is much, way more complicated on this front than Barad, but that's what I see, like, it's the, it's the assumption that she's completely egalitarian, and that her ontology is this, like, ethical thing, without question.

00:46:52.520 --> 00:47:03.820
But I'm wondering if you're not projecting a lot of that stuff, because to me, I always read, whether it's Barad or anybody else, as a provisional moment of thinking, you know, like, you're trying to figure out how to do something.

00:47:04.540 --> 00:47:10.880
Inevitably, your thing's going to be, become subject to things that you didn't want it to, you know, which is why.

00:47:11.440 --> 00:47:19.060
She hedges here and there, but it, she's pretty forceful about the, the ethical, like, implications of her project.

00:47:19.220 --> 00:47:21.660
Well, I'll say, I mean, I'll just say it this way then.

00:47:21.980 --> 00:47:28.720
For instance, the moment in Butler that I just talked about with transgender is one of the, for me, more compelling elements of Butler.

00:47:29.100 --> 00:47:34.960
She has these elements, and these elements are ones in which you don't get a sense of what you're supposed to do.

00:47:34.960 --> 00:47:50.120
You get an analytic of, you know, heteronormativity, but it's not simply the question, it's not simply an issue that that's a bad thing, but at the same time, there's plenty of implicit liberatory ethos in Butler as well.

00:47:50.120 --> 00:47:55.760
And that's the stuff from which I, I go, no, I, I also get why she does it.

00:47:55.900 --> 00:47:57.800
I also get why it's important and necessary.

00:47:57.900 --> 00:48:09.540
I don't want her not to do it, you know, I, I don't feel that way, but I also am like, that's where I'm going to not be a Butlerian, and I'm going to, you know, orient to a different, you know, a different direction.

00:48:09.720 --> 00:48:23.760
Cause to me, it's a question of like, if I can say, you know, Hegel is a symptom, I'm saying the next step for me in this case is saying it's a symptom of the problem, you know, like the big, the big problem.

00:48:23.760 --> 00:48:31.520
And so I'm interested in figuring out ways of interrupting that problem, what, what I perceive to be that problem.

00:48:32.400 --> 00:48:46.260
So that's why I wouldn't want to follow, although I'll follow it in lots of ways and in lots of places, but there is just this sort of sensibility for me that I'm like, that's the thing that needs to be stiff on, you know, the totalizing, unifying.

00:48:46.480 --> 00:48:48.960
I mean, the, the, the very slight, sorry, just real quick.

00:48:49.040 --> 00:48:54.320
The very slight difference then is that I'm more interested in simply foregrounding that problem.

00:48:54.620 --> 00:48:56.720
I think people need to interrupt it.

00:48:56.720 --> 00:49:00.700
And I think Deleuze's project, that's, that's what he's, that's the whole thing.

00:49:00.700 --> 00:49:05.020
How do you interrupt these representationalists, some of these foundations of thinking?

00:49:05.740 --> 00:49:07.500
I am just right.

00:49:07.600 --> 00:49:13.840
I mean, I understand it as a problem, but I'm a little more hesitant to, I don't know.

00:49:14.160 --> 00:49:15.480
I don't know exactly how to frame you.

00:49:15.500 --> 00:49:16.920
You want to tell other people that they're wrong.

00:49:17.200 --> 00:49:18.300
Well, right.

00:49:18.380 --> 00:49:20.080
Because we are, we are wrong.

00:49:20.440 --> 00:49:21.020
I mean, we are.

00:49:21.600 --> 00:49:28.620
But no, but now you're hypothesizing them being wrong, which is to say, I mean, that's what I'm saying is that at the end of the day,

00:49:29.000 --> 00:49:35.940
you're just telling other people that they're wrong and you have made the, them being wrong into your correctness, right?

00:49:36.060 --> 00:49:38.400
Everybody is wrong in every assertion that they make.

00:49:39.020 --> 00:49:39.460
Right.

00:49:39.700 --> 00:49:44.740
But if everybody, but if everything's a multiplicity, I mean, that's another just version of.

00:49:44.860 --> 00:49:45.300
No, no, no.

00:49:45.340 --> 00:49:46.660
That's completely untrue.

00:49:46.820 --> 00:49:48.840
No, that's where, that's, no.

00:49:48.940 --> 00:49:59.020
Because the multiplicity then just becomes a question of making another configuration, of having a force appropriate, you know, a different kind of force appropriate, whatever that mechanism is.

00:49:59.240 --> 00:50:03.840
So, no, it's not a question of saying that force is inadequate, that force is inadequate, that force.

00:50:03.840 --> 00:50:15.440
You brought up the Anti-Oedipus lying like a little bit ago.

00:50:15.440 --> 00:50:24.200
And I think it's in some ways relevant because the way that I understood your concern about we don't have to be Anti-Oedipus about everything.

00:50:25.040 --> 00:50:36.260
And then that kind of turned into the biopolitical point with Foucault was like, okay, it's not just men or women and we can have 15 different types, but they all get hypostatized and they're all subject to these other things as well.

00:50:36.320 --> 00:50:44.600
And it sounded like the critique that you wanted to run there, like, don't think that multiplicity is going to buy you into something good by getting rid of the dualism.

00:50:44.600 --> 00:50:46.500
And I completely agree with you.

00:50:46.640 --> 00:50:52.900
Like, if you do that, then, yes, you're moralizing multiplicity as simply better.

00:50:53.120 --> 00:51:05.100
And the way that I always take that Anti-Oedipus sort of mandate is that it's not that one must be Anti-Oedipus or that one must say, like, hooray, 17 different things instead of just Oedipus.

00:51:05.100 --> 00:51:15.720
It's just that the Oedipal development isn't the only thing, right, that there are other mechanisms by which things are configured.

00:51:15.920 --> 00:51:19.540
And that doesn't mean – the fact that there are more doesn't mean they're better, right?

00:51:19.680 --> 00:51:25.220
It just means that they are different and that they allow for different kinds of life, right?

00:51:25.500 --> 00:51:26.440
And we're –

00:51:26.440 --> 00:51:26.940
No, yeah, yeah.

00:51:26.940 --> 00:51:40.520
I mean, just to be clear, I don't have anything – like, I don't want to engage as if I'm simply against or, like, just really confrontational against the interrupting capacity of Deleuze or people like Foucault.

00:51:40.800 --> 00:51:43.000
I mean, I love reading their stuff as well.

00:51:43.220 --> 00:51:48.080
It's just – it doesn't feel like I have anything – it's just not quite my sensibility.

00:51:48.080 --> 00:51:53.860
I just feel like I offer something slightly – like, the more – it's just a little darker.

00:51:54.060 --> 00:51:57.600
I think I have a slightly more sinister take.

00:51:57.800 --> 00:52:00.560
Not that it's, like, more correct or anything.

00:52:00.700 --> 00:52:01.860
It's just a different take.

00:52:01.960 --> 00:52:02.300
Bullshit.

00:52:02.320 --> 00:52:03.160
You know what I mean?

00:52:03.340 --> 00:52:03.780
Bullshit.

00:52:03.940 --> 00:52:04.340
What?

00:52:04.920 --> 00:52:06.640
Of course it's that it's more correct.

00:52:07.080 --> 00:52:08.360
Of course that's the engine.

00:52:08.940 --> 00:52:09.660
Why would I assume –

00:52:09.660 --> 00:52:11.040
You want to tell other people they're wrong.

00:52:11.360 --> 00:52:14.400
Well, I do want to do that, but, like, that doesn't mean they're wrong.

00:52:14.500 --> 00:52:15.040
You know what I mean?

00:52:15.060 --> 00:52:17.480
Like, I think the critique can be generative.

00:52:17.480 --> 00:52:22.920
I don't know why – I don't see why that has to be a stopping point, telling people they're wrong.

00:52:22.940 --> 00:52:25.560
Okay, but, no, here's my – here's a real question.

00:52:26.060 --> 00:52:33.420
In the case of, let's say, Barad or whatever thing, telling them that they're wrong, what – let's imagine – what does that generate?

00:52:33.420 --> 00:52:38.620
I'm generating a critique that's – my reading of Barad is not out there.

00:52:38.940 --> 00:52:40.700
I mean, you could see that from the proposal.

00:52:40.880 --> 00:52:42.540
Nobody's reading Barad like that.

00:52:43.260 --> 00:52:43.600
I mean –

00:52:43.600 --> 00:52:44.120
Okay, good.

00:52:44.280 --> 00:52:45.520
So, it – so, fine.

00:52:45.760 --> 00:52:47.300
So, it generates a career.

00:52:47.800 --> 00:52:48.480
Okay, what else?

00:52:49.120 --> 00:52:51.860
What else am I supposed to be generating right now?

00:52:53.440 --> 00:52:55.060
New forms of fucking life, man.

00:52:55.080 --> 00:52:56.140
That's what we're talking about.

00:52:56.560 --> 00:52:56.740
Right?

00:52:56.820 --> 00:52:58.220
Like, that's – so, here's what that does.

00:52:58.420 --> 00:53:05.100
That completely takes its position in, you know, obviously, like, the kind of intellectual trajectory.

00:53:05.280 --> 00:53:07.440
And that's – there's not – I'm not criticizing that.

00:53:07.480 --> 00:53:08.640
I'm not saying that's a bad thing.

00:53:08.680 --> 00:53:10.240
And we all have pragmatic concerns.

00:53:10.800 --> 00:53:16.580
But I'm just saying, like, what's the end point other than you get a dissertation, you get a book, you get whatever.

00:53:16.820 --> 00:53:17.120
Right, right.

00:53:17.180 --> 00:53:18.580
I mean, I don't know.

00:53:18.700 --> 00:53:21.320
I mean, clearly, parts of it are just sort of selfish.

00:53:21.500 --> 00:53:24.540
I mean, listen, that – like, at the beginning of –

00:53:24.540 --> 00:53:25.400
Nothing wrong with being selfish.

00:53:25.420 --> 00:53:26.700
I'm not critiquing selfishness.

00:53:26.940 --> 00:53:29.240
I'm asking the – I'm asking in terms of the thinking.

00:53:29.640 --> 00:53:29.880
Right?

00:53:29.960 --> 00:53:33.360
Like, it's not – I'm not – I'm so not saying you're selfish.

00:53:33.360 --> 00:53:33.800
No, I know.

00:53:34.020 --> 00:53:34.860
I mean, I don't know.

00:53:35.380 --> 00:53:36.980
I just don't think it goes anywhere.

00:53:36.980 --> 00:53:46.980
I think it stops at the point of whether it's you or somebody else assuming a position that is the next in, like, you are the responder to Zizek.

00:53:47.380 --> 00:53:50.240
And then so and so is the responder to you responding to Zizek.

00:53:50.440 --> 00:53:58.280
And so it creates – to me, it just creates a tradition or a legacy in a very, very straightforward sense.

00:53:58.660 --> 00:54:02.680
And it doesn't – what it doesn't do is create different possibilities for thinking.

00:54:02.820 --> 00:54:03.520
It doesn't do that.

00:54:03.520 --> 00:54:07.960
Well, I mean, maybe for my – maybe it does sort of hypothesize for myself.

00:54:08.100 --> 00:54:12.260
But I think even the reaction against that creates something.

00:54:12.460 --> 00:54:13.960
It's got to create something.

00:54:14.200 --> 00:54:15.060
Yes, it does.

00:54:15.180 --> 00:54:21.440
All of the things that I'm laying out are things, but they're things that are sort of – they're cogs in a machine that already exists.

00:54:21.560 --> 00:54:23.560
It's not – it doesn't go laterally.

00:54:23.640 --> 00:54:25.040
It just goes, you know, vertically.

00:54:25.500 --> 00:54:31.620
Maybe I've just committed to the Barad thing at this point, and that's sort of why I'm still attaching to that line.

00:54:31.620 --> 00:54:32.440
But I don't know.

00:54:32.700 --> 00:54:42.180
I do think there is, as a trend, if you could say there are Baradians that are not Barad, that are doing something with a similar sensibility.

00:54:42.320 --> 00:54:44.120
They're not empiricists, like you said.

00:54:44.480 --> 00:54:47.340
But they are confident in their propositional content.

00:54:47.620 --> 00:54:53.480
The style, the way they articulate the conceptual stuff, and the confidence in the ethical comportment.

00:54:53.720 --> 00:54:56.600
I think – I think those things are ridiculous.

00:54:57.400 --> 00:55:08.040
Like – and I'm not saying that, like, my way of thinking is – now you should pick mine, as opposed to Barad's, pick my way of thinking.

00:55:08.040 --> 00:55:14.220
Now, I mean, that's completely antithetical to the whole project, which is to say don't hypostasize a position.

00:55:14.640 --> 00:55:21.780
Constantly suspend positions, and even that, there's no guarantee that that leads to something productive or ethical.

00:55:22.240 --> 00:55:29.580
It's just – I mean, like, maybe I am, you know, doing a version of hypostasizing here, but I don't know.

00:55:29.680 --> 00:55:36.560
I think that suspension is useful, and it's not a sensibility that I've seen offered in our field, at least.

00:55:36.920 --> 00:55:43.020
Zizek certainly offers it, but, you know, it's not in rhetoric, really.

00:55:43.500 --> 00:56:00.360
Well, that raises a really important question and sort of trajectory for the project, is that if what you really care about is sort of, like, demonstrating the danger of the hypostasizing moment and the danger of the proposition as, like, a moment of thinking,

00:56:01.580 --> 00:56:10.960
I wonder if that point doesn't get missed if you focus on the specific content of what Barad specifically is wrong about.

00:56:11.120 --> 00:56:16.620
Because then people aren't focusing on the structures of thinking that leads to this kind of thing.

00:56:16.680 --> 00:56:27.520
They're like, ah, well, Barad was wrong with these particular propositions, so all I need to do is come up with some new ones in order to reground my faith in this orientation.

00:56:28.440 --> 00:56:39.240
Correctness, but it's, like, it's all driven by a kind of correctness, and trying to, I mean, that's the thing that's hard to, if not impossible, to undermine is, like, stop trying to get it done.

00:56:39.480 --> 00:56:57.140
But it seems like, intellectually speaking, what you care about more is thinking about Barad as a particular symptom of thinking, right?

00:56:57.500 --> 00:57:02.220
And not her or her arguments in particular.

00:57:02.440 --> 00:57:18.100
So, like, you could still write about Barad and say, like, look at the, like, look, we're going to, I'm going to read Barad not as a thinker of correctness, but as a symptom of a particular style of thinking that, you know, like, produced as these kinds of productions.

00:57:18.900 --> 00:57:35.260
But then it could become, like, but that doesn't make her work totally uninteresting, and what would happen, like, what would a suspension of certainty look like if it were run through the Barad again machine?

00:57:35.660 --> 00:57:37.300
And does that produce anything interesting?

00:57:37.440 --> 00:57:44.380
Now, suddenly, Barad becomes both a symptom of this danger that you want to demonstrate, and a way out.

00:57:44.680 --> 00:57:45.300
And a way out.

00:57:45.340 --> 00:57:47.920
No, it's just the idea of the internal critique as well.

00:57:48.040 --> 00:57:56.420
I mean, the goal will be to, Barad has the key to her critique in her own language, in the conceptual systems.

00:57:56.740 --> 00:58:01.080
It's just that she doesn't fully unravel some of those implications.

00:58:01.080 --> 00:58:03.780
I totally, she's not Derridean enough in that regard.

00:58:07.440 --> 00:58:18.380
Let me, let me go, because this is the passage that I was going to choose, and it's exactly what we're talking about, because I was, I was struggling over this passage, and this is paragraph 29.

00:58:18.840 --> 00:58:31.960
He's just gone through the individual, spirit-individual relation that Nathaniel got us to, and science sets forth, it's a couple sentences down, but I'll start with science sets forth this formative process.

00:58:31.960 --> 00:58:49.500
So what science does is it, it sets out this, the, that sort of, the dialectical, you know, interiorization, externalization, this formative process in all its detail and necessity, exposing the mature configuration of everything which has already been reduced to a moment and property of spirit.

00:58:49.600 --> 00:58:58.500
So spirit's gone, you know, to like point, you know, Y or Z or whatever, and it shows you the ABCs along the way.

00:58:58.700 --> 00:59:02.160
The goal is spirit's insight into what knowing is.

00:59:03.160 --> 00:59:08.640
Impatience demands the impossible, to wit, the attainment of the end without the means, right?

00:59:08.660 --> 00:59:13.280
